llets (about 6 oz each)\n- 1/2 cup all-purpose flour\n- Salt and white pepper to taste\n- 4 tbsp butter, divided\n-\n\nNow I'm generating the second recipe file for sole meunière, another traditional dish. I'll continue with the ingredient list and then provide cooking instructions that emphasize the technique of creating brown butter and the proper pan-searing method for delicate fish fillets.\n\n2 tbsp fresh lemon juice\n- Fresh parsley for garnish\n\nINSTRUCTIONS:\n1. Pat sole fillets dry with paper towels. Season with salt and pepper.\n2. Dust fillets lightly with flour, shaking off excess.\n3. Heat 2 tbsp butter in a large skillet over medium-high heat.\n4. Cook fillets 3-4 minutes per side until golden and opaque.\n5. Transfer to a warm plate.\n6. Add remaining butter to skillet and cook until it turns golden brown.\n7. Drizzle browned butter and lemon juice over fillets.\n8. Garnish with fresh parsley and serve immediately.\n\nSERVING SUGGESTIONS:\nServe with steamed asparagus and new potatoes.\n```\n\n**File 3: Scallop and Saffron Risotto.generated.22.txt** (SPLIT_TITLE)\n```\nSCALLOP AND\nSAFFRON\nRISOTTO\n\nA luxurious risotto showcasing the delicate sweetness of bay scallops paired\nwith the golden, aromatic notes of saffron. This dish is perfect for\nentertaining special guests.\n\nINGREDIENTS:\n- 1 lb large scallops\n- 6 cups chicken or seafood stock, warmed\n- 1 small pinch saffron threads\n-\n\n1/4 cup white wine\n- 1 shallot, minced\n- 1 1/2 cups arborio rice\n- 2 tbsp butter\n- 1/4 cup grated Parmesan cheese\n- 2 tbsp olive oil\n- Salt and pepper to taste\n\nINSTRUCTIONS:\n1. Steep saffron threads in 1/4 cup warm stock for 10 minutes to infuse color and flavor.\n2. Heat olive oil in a large pot over medium heat, then sauté minced shallot until softened, about 2 minutes.\n3. Add rice and stir constantly for 1-2 minutes until the edges turn translucent.\n4. Pour in white wine and stir until fully absorbed.\n5. Begin adding warm stock one ladle at a time, stirring frequently and allowing each addition to absorb before adding more.\n6. After 12 minutes, pat scallops dry, season with salt and pepper, then sear them in a separate skillet for 2 minutes per side and set aside.\n7. Continue adding stock until the rice becomes creamy and tender, then fold in the seared scallops, butter, and Parmesan to finish.\n\n**File 4: Kompot Jabłkowy.generated.22.txt** (SPLIT_TITLE)\n```\nKOMPOT\nJABŁKOWY\n\nKompot is a traditional Polish fruit drink, served hot or cold as a refreshing\nbeverage. This apple version is simple, wholesome, and perfect for any season.\n\nINGREDIENTS:\n- 4 cups fresh apple juice or 8 medium apples, sliced\n- 6 cups water\n- 1/2 cup sugar\n- 3 cloves\n- 1 cinnamon stick\n- 1/4 tsp nutmeg\n- Juice of 1/2 lemon\n\nINSTRUCTIONS:\n1. If using whole apples, peel, core, and slice them into thin wedges.\n2. Combine water and sugar in a large pot and bring to boil.\n3. Add apples (or apple juice), cloves, cinnamon stick, and nutmeg.\n4. Reduce heat and simmer 15-20 minutes until the apples soften and flavors meld together. Finish with fresh lemon juice and serve warm or chilled.\n\nSERVING SUGGESTIONS:\nServe as a refreshing drink alongside meals or as a light dessert.\n```\n\n**File 5: Pan Seared Cod.generated.22.txt** (METADATA_PREFIX)\n```\nJesień | Dania główne | Dla 4 osób\n\nPAN SEARED COD\n\nThis simple preparation allows the delicate, flaky texture of cod to shine.\nThe golden crust from pan-searing contrasts beautifully with the tender flesh\ninside. A perfect weeknight dinner.\n\nINGREDIENTS:\n- 4 cod fillets (6 oz each)\n- Salt and pepper to taste\n- 3 tbsp olive oil\n- 2 tbsp butter\n- 3 cloves garlic, minced\n- Juice of 1 lemon\n- Fresh thyme sprigs\n\nINSTRUCTIONS:\n1. Pat cod fillets completely dry with paper towels.\n2. Season generously on both sides with salt and pepper.\n3. Heat olive oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat until just smoking.\n4. Carefully place cod skin-side down in the pan.\n5. Resist the urge to move the fish—let it cook undisturbed for 4-5 minutes.\n6. Using a thin spatula, gently flip the fillets.\n7. Add butter, garlic, and thyme sprigs to the pan.\n8. Cook another 3-4 minutes until fish is opaque throughout.\n9. Finish with fresh lemon juice.\n\nPair this with roasted root vegetables or a crisp green salad for a complete meal.\n\n**File 6: Kopytka z Grzybami.generated.22.txt** (METADATA_PREFIX)\n```\nZima | Dania główne | Przygotowanie 20 min | Gotowanie 15 min\n\nKOPYTKA Z GRZYBAMI\n\nKopytka, meaning \"little hooves,\" are small Polish dumplings resembling their namesake. Tossed with sautéed mushrooms and caramelized onions, this dish is hearty comfort food at its finest.\n\nINGREDIENTS:\n- 1 1/2 lbs kopytka (or gnocchi)\n- 1 lb mixed mushrooms, sliced\n- 2 large onions, thinly sliced\n- 3 tbsp butter, divided\n- 2 cloves garlic, minced\n- 1/2 cup sour cream\n- Salt and pepper to taste\n- Fresh dill for garnish\n\nINSTRUCTIONS:\n1. Bring a large pot of salted water to boil. Cook kopytka until they float plus 2 minutes.\n2. In a large skillet, melt 1 tbsp butter over medium-high heat.\n3. Sauté onions until deep golden brown, about 20 minutes. Set aside.\n4. In the same skillet, melt remaining butter and add mushrooms.\n5. Cook mushrooms until golden and liquid has evaporated, about 8 minutes.\n6. Add garlic and cook 1 minute more.\n7. Stir in cooked kopytka and caramelized onions.\n8. Lower heat and stir in sour cream. Season with salt and pepper.\n9. Heat through gently without boiling.\n10. Garnish with fresh dill before serving.\n\nSERVING SUGGESTIONS:\nServe alongside roasted root vegetables or a crisp green salad.\n\n**File 7: Lavender Panna Cotta.generated.22.txt** (METADATA_PREFIX)\n```\nWiosna | Desery | Dla 6 osób | Przygotowanie 15 min | Chłodzenie 4 godziny\n\nLAVENDER PANNA COTTA\n\nA silky, delicate dessert with subtle floral lavender notes—elegant yet surprisingly simple to prepare. This refined treat works beautifully for intimate dinners or outdoor celebrations. Combine heavy cream, whole milk, sugar, and dried culinary lavender buds, then bloom gelatin in cold water before folding everything together and chilling for four hours until set.\n\nINGREDIENTS:\n- 2 cups heavy cream\n- 1/2 cup whole milk\n- 1/4 cup sugar\n- 1 tbsp dried culinary lavender buds\n- 1 tsp vanilla extract\n- 2 tsp gelatin\n- 3 tbsp cold water\n- Honey for drizzling\n\nINSTRUCTIONS:\n1. Combine cream, milk, sugar, and lavender buds in a saucepan.\n2. Heat gently over medium, stirring occasionally, until steaming. Do not boil.\n3. Remove from heat and let steep 30 minutes.\n4. Strain through a fine mesh sieve, pressing gently on lavender. Discard solids.\n5. Bloom gelatin in cold water for 5 minutes.\n6. Reheat cream mixture gently and whisk in bloomed gelatin until completely dissolved.\n7. Stir in vanilla extract.\n8. Pour into serving glasses or small ramekins.\n9. Chill at least 4 hours until set.\n10. Top with honey and serve cold.\n```\n\n**File 8: Ogórkowa Zupa.generated.22.txt** (METADATA_PREFIX)\n```\nLato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | PRZYGOTOWANIE 15 MIN | GOTOWANIE 20 MIN\n\nOGÓRKOWA ZUPA\n\nThis Polish cucumber soup offers refreshing versatility—serve it hot during cooler months or chilled on warm summer days. The dill-infused broth is bright and tan\n\n, light yet satisfying.\n\nINGREDIENTS:\n- 6 medium cucumbers, peeled and diced\n- 6 cups vegetable or chicken stock\n- 1 large onion, diced\n- 2 tbsp butter\n- 2 cloves garlic, minced\n- 3 tbsp fresh dill, chopped\n- 2 tbsp fresh lemon juice\n- 1/2 cup sour cream\n- Salt and pepper to taste\n\nINSTRUCTIONS:\n1. Melt butter in a large pot over medium heat.\n2. Sauté onion until translucent, about 5 minutes.\n3. Add garlic and cook 1 minute more.\n4. Add diced cucumbers and cook for 3 minutes.\n5. Pour in stock and bring to a simmer.\n6. Simmer for 15 minutes until cucumbers are tender.\n7. Add fresh dill and lemon juice.\n8. Season with salt and pepper.\n9. For creamy version, stir in sour cream just before serving.\n10. Serve hot or chill and serve cold with a dollop of sour cream.\n```\n\n**File 9: Osso Buco.generated.22.txt** (OCR_CORRUPTION)\n```\nOSSO BUCO\n\nA classic Italian braise of veal shanks in white wine and tomato sauce, where slow cooking transforms the meat into something incredibly tender while the sauce develops deep, complex flavors. \"Osso b\n\nuco\" means \"bone with hole\" - referring to the marrow bone. The dish requires browning the shanks first, then building a vegetable and wine base before the long braise. Key ingredients include veal shanks, white wine, beef or veal stock, crushed tomatoes, aromatic vegetables, tomato paste, and herbs like bay leaf and thyme. The shanks are seasoned, floured, and browned on all sides before being set aside, then onions, carrots, celery, and garlic are sautéed in the same pot to develop flavor.\n\nOnce the aromatics are softened, tomato paste goes in for depth, followed by white wine to deglaze and capture the browned bits. The crushed tomatoes and stock are added along with bay leaf and thyme, then the shanks nestle back into the pot among the vegetables. The whole thing braises covered in a 350°F oven for 2.5 to 3 hours until the meat is tender and nearly falling from the bone. The sauce can be reduced if needed, and the finished shanks are served with sauce spooned over, typically alongside risotto. A gremolata of fresh parsley, lemon zest, and minced garlic makes an optional but traditional garnish.\n\nThis Polish poppy seed cake combines ground poppy seeds with chopped dried plums for a dense, flavorful cake that works well with coffee or tea. The ingredient list includes flour, poppy seed filling, dried plums, sugar, melted butter, eggs, sour cream, baking powder, vanilla, salt, and optional plum jam for topping. The method begins by preheating the oven to 350°F and preparing a loaf pan, then creaming sugar with melted butter before beating in eggs one at a time.\n\nThen add vanilla, fold in the poppy seed filling and sour cream alternately with the flour mixture, and gently stir in the chopped plums and baking powder. Pour the batter into the prepared pan and bake for 45-50 minutes until a toothpick inserted in the center comes out clean. Let it cool in the pan for 15 minutes before turning it out, and optionally brush the warm cake with plum jam for added sweetness. The cake keeps well wrapped at room temperature for three days or can be frozen for up to a month, served at room temperature or slightly warmed.\n\nI need to verify I have the right file count and types. Checking against the requirements: four SPLIT_TITLE files, four METADATA_PREFIX files, and two OCR_CORRUPTION files for a total of ten. My list includes Piernik z Orzechami, Sole Meunière, Scallop and Saffron Risotto, and Kompot Jabłkowy as SPLIT_TITLE entries; Pan Seared Cod, Kopytka z Grzybami, Lavender Panna Cotta, and Ogórkowa Zupa as METADATA_PREFIX entries; and Osso Buco and Makowiec ze Śliwkami as OCR_CORRUPTION entries. That's the correct distribution.\n\nNow I'll create these files using the Write tool, batching the calls where feasible to be efficient.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":76912,"cache_read_input_tokens":15568,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":76912},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"31f79979-f917-445a-83c4-99cb8a3cfd6e","uuid":"90353b25-0409-42a4-8a8d-c59e660aad52"}
